<li id="lithub_daily_widget-9" class="widget widget_lithub_daily_widget"><div class="lithub-daily-header"><a href="/category/lit-hub-daily/"><b>Lithub</b> Daily</a></div><h2 class="widgettitle">July 15, 2024</h2>
<a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hub-daily-july-15-2024/"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-239926 size-thumbnail" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Jaws-150x150.png" alt="jaws" width="150" height="150" /></a>
<ul>
 	<li><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/07/12/books/booksupdate/jaws-peter-benchley-50.html" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">Brian Raftery on </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400">Jaws </span></i><span style="font-weight: 400">at fifty</span></a></li>
 	<li><a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2024/07/12/alice-munro-abuse-canada-reckoning/" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">Literature professors are grappling with how to teach Alice Munro</span></a></li>
 	<li><a href="https://jacobin.com/2024/07/argentina-media-union-milei-telam/" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">How Argentinian journalists and media workers fought far-right politics</span></a></li>
</ul>
